Ford GoBike System Data Analysis¶

by Abdallah Aboudeif¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset comes in one csv file that consists of 15 columns that have a data of about 183400 bike trips

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

There are many interesting features:

  • Trip duration
  • Member gender
  • Member birth year

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • Start time
  • Member type

In [25]:
# visualizing trip durations using 'Logarithmic Scales' method
log_binsize = 0.05
duration_bins = 10 ** np.arange(2, np.log10(df.duration_min.max()) + log_binsize, log_binsize)
plt.figure(figsize = [14, 7])
plt.hist(data = df, x = 'duration_min', bins = duration_bins, color='purple')
plt.title('Trip Durations Distribution', y=1.05, size = 20)
plt.xlabel('Trip Durations by minutes', size = 10)
plt.ylabel('Trip Count log', size = 10);

Here, we can notice that the number of longer durations trips is less, and in general the number of trips increases with the shorter duration

In [27]:
# visualizing the distribution of trip numbers over day hours
df['start_hour'] = df['start_hour'].apply(lambda x: 24 if x == 0 else x)
plt.figure(figsize = [14, 7])
sns.countplot(data=df, x='start_hour', color='orange')
plt.title('Trip numbers over day hours', y=1.05, size = 20)
plt.xlabel('Day hours', size = 10)
plt.ylabel('Trip number', size = 10);

We can notice here that the number of trips of longer times is less, and in general the number of trips increases with the shorter duration.

6- What is the distribution of trips number week days ?¶

The dataset provides us with trips start time in date-time format that we can use in order to extract the trip start week day number and converting it to day name which could be visualize the distribution of trips number over week days.

In [28]:
# extracting the trip start week day number and converting it to day name
weekday = ['Mon', 'Tue', 'Wed', 'Thu', 'Fri', 'Sat', 'Sun']
df['start_day'] = df.start_time.dt.dayofweek
df['dayofweek'] = df['start_day'].apply(lambda x: weekday[x])
df_dayofweek = df.groupby(['dayofweek']).size().reset_index()
df_dayofweek.head(5)

In [29]:
# visualizing the distribution of trips over week days
plt.figure(figsize = [14, 7])
sns.pointplot(data=df_dayofweek, x='dayofweek', y=0, color='green', order = weekday);
plt.title('The distribution of trips over week days')
plt.xlabel('Weekdays')
plt.ylabel('Number of trips');

It is possible to notice here that the number of trips is at their highest levels on Thursday, while they are at their lowest levels on Saturday and Sunday, and for the rest of the week, the rate of trips is close to each other

Bivariate Exploration¶

In this section, we will investigate relationships between pairs of variables in our data. This includes the distribution of trips changes over the week days according to user type, the distribution of trips changes over the day hours according to user's gender and the relationship between the percentages of male and female users for each day of the week.

1- Does the distribution of trips changes over the week days according to user type?¶

In [30]:
# visualizing the distribution of trips changing over the week days according to user type
plt.figure(figsize=[ 16,5])
sns.countplot(data = df , x = 'dayofweek',hue = 'user_type',order = weekday);
plt.title('Distribution of trips over week days for each user type')
plt.xlabel('Week days')
plt.ylabel('Number of trips')
plt.xticks(rotation = 90);

We can see that the distribution of trips for each day of the week is influenced by the type of user, for subscribed users this rate changes to form the same graph for the users as a whole, and for non-subscribed users the rate of trips is almost constant for all days of the week.

2- Does the distribution of trips changes over the day hours according to user's gender?¶

In [31]:
# visualizing the distribution of trips changes over the day hours according to user's gender
plt.figure(figsize=[ 16, 8])
sns.countplot(data = df , x = 'start_hour',hue = 'member_gender');
plt.title('Distribution of User Type by day hours')
plt.xlabel('Day hours')
plt.ylabel('Number of trips')
plt.xticks(rotation = 90);
plt.draw()

We can see that the distribution of the number of trips per hour of the day is almost the same for male and female users, although the number of male users is greater as mentioned above, but for non-gender-specific users, the pattern of trip distribution is almost constant.

3- What is the relationship between the percentages of male and female users for each day of the week?¶

To create dataset shows the relationship between the percentages of male and female users for each day of the week, we must first calculate these percentages for each gender separately and put them together in a dataset, then represent the dataset in heat map.

In [32]:
# calculating the rate of trips frequency for male and female users
males_trips = df[df['member_gender'] == 'Male'].dayofweek
females_trips = df[df['member_gender'] == 'Female'].dayofweek
males_proportion = males_trips.value_counts() / len(males_trips)
females_proportion = females_trips.value_counts() / len(females_trips)
In [33]:
# creating trips frequency rate dataframe
mixed = pd.DataFrame([males_proportion,females_proportion]).T.reindex(weekday)
mixed.columns = ['Males','Females']
mixed.head(5)
Out[33]:

# visualizing the distribution of member gender's proportion by week days

sns.heatmap(mixed,annot = True,cmap='RdYlGn')
plt.title("Distribution of Member Gender's proportion by week days")
plt.xlabel('Member Gender')
plt.ylabel('Week days');

We can see here just by looking that the percentages of males and females members for each day of the week is approximately the same for male and female members with slight difference.

# merging duration and count dataframes in one dataframe
df_mixed = pd.merge(duration, count, on="dayofweek")
df_mixed.columns = ['dayofweek','duration','count']
df_mixed['duration'] = df_mixed['duration'] / df_mixed['duration'].sum()
df_mixed['count'] = df_mixed['count'] / df_mixed['count'].sum()
df_mixed.index = df_mixed['dayofweek']
df_mixed.drop(columns=['dayofweek'],inplace = True)

To answer the question that we previously asked, Is the reason for the increase in the total number of trips on Thursdays and Tuesdays due to the increase and decrease in the number of trips on those days? In general, what we found when we compared the average number of trips to trips duration for each day of the week is that they have similar increase and decreases pattern. We found that that pattern is slightly different, for example, trips on Saturdays and Sundays have a higher rate of duration than the rest of week days compared to the number of trips, while the duration rate decreases on the rest of week days compared to the average number of trips.
